		<header>
			
			<h1>Obstacles remain to growth of regional food trade in Eastern and Southern Africa</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The East African Community’s Common Market, created on 1 July this year, is a big step in the development of cross-border trade, and there are signs that it is starting to grow roots. Nevertheless, recent press reports show that many obstacles still lie across the path of regional commerce throughout Eastern and Southern Africa.</p><p>In 2009, the Great Lakes region already accounted for 46% of Uganda’s exports, the country’s four largest trading partners being Sudan, Kenya, Rwanda and Democratic Republic of Congo. It is of little surprise therefore that Uganda shows open enthusiasm for regional integration.</p><p>Uniting forces with neighbours means ‘having an advantage on trade returns because of a larger market, which is capable of consuming goods and services produced locally,’ said state planning minister Ephraim Kamuntu in October.</p><p>Not all Ugandans appear to agree. At Busia, the bustling border point for Uganda’s food trade with Kenya, local traders complain that they are losing business as Kenyan merchants are now buying fish, maize and beans directly from Ugandan producers. However, this is a clear sign that Ugandan and Kenyan markets are beginning to integrate.</p><p>And not a day too soon, judging by the World Bank’s figures. Obiageli Ezekwesili, the Bank’s vice-president for Africa, reported recently that only 10% of African trade is conducted within the continent, compared to about 60% in western Europe, half a century after Europe’s Common Market was started.</p><p>Tanzania seems to be in a good position to benefit from the new Common Market after a bumper crop of 12.8 million tonnes of food this year, including a 38% increase in the maize crop to 4.73 million tonnes. The millet crop rose 31% to 1.18 million tonnes and sorghum by 33% to 1.12 million tonnes, alongside substantially higher production of potatoes, cassava and plantains, according to agriculture minister Stephen Wassira.</p><p>This means an estimated surplus for export of 1.4 million tonnes of food, including 199,000 tonnes of maize and 441,000 tonnes of rice, justifying the government’s lifting of its export ban in October, although wheat, sorghum and millet remain in deficit.</p><p>However, elsewhere it is not proving so easy. After a good harvest Kenya has considered lifting its own maize export ban. But forecasts of lower than usual short rains in October-December this year and possible drought in 2011 have led the government to double the grain reserve’s requirement to 8 million bags of 90 kg.</p><p>And the development of Kenya’s trade with Ethiopia has also gone less smoothly, as Kenya has asked the COMESA secretariat to arbitrate over the list of products that can be traded across the two countries’ border.</p><p>Familiar technical problems also remain. Traditionally, South Africa is an important maize supplier to its African neighbours, and this year it achieved the biggest maize harvest for at least 50 years at 13.6 million tonnes, according to the US Department of Agriculture.</p><p>However, the deterioration of South Africa’s railways and the strength of the rand led the USDA to halve the maize export forecast for the 2010-11 crop year to 2 million tonnes. Rail now carries less than 30% of South Africa’s grain crop from the silos, compared with 85% in the early 1990s.</p>
		
		
