				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>One of the objectives of the establishment of the EAC Common Market is to sustain the expansion and integration of economic activities as well as to strengthen, coordinate and regulate the economic and trade relations among the Partner States, in order to promote accelerated growth.</p><p>The press articles underlying the trading experiences above highlight that in order to facilitate the objective of cross-border trade, certain measures have to be in place. There is a price to deeper regional integration, with the risk of some stakeholders losing out, such as the Ugandan traders at Busia (whose role as middlemen has become redundant), but with gains for other stakeholders, such as producers and consumers.</p><p>Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Burundi and Rwanda will need to pursue trade facilitation measures vigorously if they are to reap the full benefits of the common market. Many African countries conduct very little trade among themselves, but Uganda is an exception to this on the continent, with about 46% of its exports going to its neighbours. There are many reasons which impede trade among developing countries, including, <i>inter alia</i>, lower regional prices, high transaction costs and poor infrastructure, and especially transportation. This sector is very capital intensive, requiring huge investments, which are sometimes not budgeted for.</p><p>Cereal production is in its nature very cyclical in rain-fed systems, with surplus or shortages occurring frequently. Countries seek export markets in times of bumper crops but governments may tend to close borders (sometimes without notice) during shortages, in order to secure domestic supplies and maximise national food security. These issues underline the importance, particularly where food is concerned, of carefully considering the implications for stakeholders throughout the supply chain when moving to new trading mechanisms such as regional common markets.</p><p>﻿</p>
		</div>
		
